<text font="CMU Serif Medium" size="17.675559" x="11.432564" y="8.883774" color="#000000ff" ts="0" fn="">Question: How to look at wavefunction amplitudes across different sites, with independant trials of different sites?

One solution is to not have independant trials of different sites, but this will diminish the quality of our data,
I think. We're currently taking one or two bonds per video, and when we do two bonds, we don't take different
combinations, so we can't do a chain of phase relations.
</text>
<text font="CMU Serif Medium" size="19" x="16.899548" y="360.14629" color="#000000ff" ts="0" fn="">And this doesn't require overlapping videos. I suppose then, our strategy could be something like this:
- Look at any mode we like. Say, the top mode, which should be one of the 'cleaner' ones. We look at the leftmost
  pair of blocks, which we can get in one video, at least, this is what we had for all the topological data I took. 
- Take the complex FFT, and look at the wavefunction amplitudes for the top site. I think we can set the leftmost
mode to be real since global phase shift doesn't matter, and this sets the phase of the 2nd site's top mode as well,
as well as the phases of all other modes within these two blocks. 
- Looking at the next datasets, we normalize to force the correct SSH phase on the top mode, and all other modes then
automatically get normalized and phase-fixed. This might be slightly circular? (but, not really?), but in any case
for our own verification... let's see it!</text>
